content.description: Follow the 4 bolts up on the right side of the Calcium Fortified Rock, the crux is making a move off the bench at the third bolt.
content.protection: 4 bolts and chains at the top.
content.location: From the dirt parking lot, follow the main trail past the Don Quixote Face and Secondary Wall a few hundred yards until the main trail begins to go left up a gully.  Halfway up the gully on the right you will see the obvious rock outcrop that is called the Calcium Fortified Rock.  The route is located on the right side of the rock.

content.description:
Start on the far left by a serviceberry bush.  Negotiate past some slopers to a rail, then past some thin moves to a crimper rail.  Many eliminates possible.

Called V2 (and "a good endurance test for intermediates") by Sherman in Stone Crusade.  Called V3 in a later guide.  You decide.
content.protection: It's a traverse, you can go padless like generations did before...
content.location: In the bouldering corridors to the right and below the main face.

content.description: Easy boulder problem. Just to the right of the gold and yellow spray paint. You can either dyno to the top of the "nipple" or use the arÃªte to the right side. Great route to practice dyno confidence.
Slab problem in Spokane?! Start out with a double undercling above the "BUNS" spray paint. Move out left and then up to a decent top out.
content.location: This is the left-most problem on what I'm pretty sure is called the Morning Cooler Rock in the Marty Bland guide book. From the parking lot take the wood stairs up and stay on the main trail until you get to a fork in the trail near the main wall (left goes to Smokey on Fire). Take a right and soon after is the Morning Cooler Rock, it will be on your right. There are 3 distinct slab problems on this wall, this one is the left-most problem.

content.description:
Follow the narrow, slightly overhanging nose up a straight-forward start. The crux is between the third and fourth bolt: crimps to a sloping jug and a mantel to an inclined, easy finish.

Very short, but fun route.
content.protection: Four bolts (appearing new) to chains. Lower-off.
content.location: Follow the path above the secondary wall west (past the top-anchors for climbs like the Prow). On your right you'll see a couple small jutting rock faces with bolts. Walk past these about a hundred yards. You'll see an incline with a narrow aggressive boulder and two bolted routes visible from the path. Freeing South Africa is the right-most route following the nose of the rock.

content.description: Start on the undercling and throw out over the roof.  It's a pretty fair throw.
content.location: This is on the Eddy Wall which is located just north of Dirk Diggler.

content.description: Located on the left side of the Calcium Fortified Rock.  Starts up good jugs to clip the first bolt, then move through the overhung crux to clip your second bolt.  After that make your way up to the chains.
content.protection: 4 bolts and chains at the top.
content.location: From the dirt parking lot, head out past the Don Quixote Face on the obvious trail, stay low on the trail until a major trail goes up the hill on the left in a gully.  About half way up the gully you will see an obvious rock outcrop on your right which is the Calcium Fortified Rock.  Located on the left side of the Calcium Fortified Rock.
